         neurons were lost, as in HD. Together these data argue that dysfunction within                    the STN is an early feature of HD that may contribute to its expression and                    course.</p>            </abstract>            <kwd-group kwd-group-type="research-organism">                <title>Research organism</title>                <kwd>Mouse</kwd>            </kwd-group>            <funding-group>                <award-group id="par-1">                    <funding-source>                        <institution-wrap>                            <institution-id institution-id-type="FundRef">http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/100005725</institution-id>                            <institution>CHDI Foundation</institution>                        </institution-wrap>                    </funding-source>                    <principal-award-recipient>                        <name>                            <surname>Atherton</surname>                            <given-names>Jeremy F</given-names>                        </name>                        <name>                            <surname>Bevan</surname>                            <given-names>Mark D</given-names>                        </name>                    </principal-award-recipient>                </award-group>                <award-group id="par-2">                    <funding-source>                        <institution-wrap>                            <institution-id institution-id-type="FundRef">http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/100000002</institution-id>                            <institution>National Institutes of Health</institution>                        </institution-wrap>                    </funding-source>                    <award-id>2R37 NS041280 and 2P50 NS047085</award-id>                    <principal-award-recipient>                        <name>                            <surname>McIver</surname>                            <given-names>Eileen L</given-names>                        </na